description:
DOM = Document Object Model — the browser's in-memory tree of HTML elements.

SELECTING ELEMENTS:
  document.getElementById('id')
  document.querySelector('.class')      // first match
  document.querySelectorAll('div')      // NodeList of all

MODIFYING ELEMENTS:
  el.textContent = 'new text';          // safe (escapes HTML)
  el.innerHTML   = '<b>bold</b>';       // renders HTML (XSS risk)
  el.style.color = 'red';
  el.classList.add('active');
  el.classList.toggle('hidden');
  el.setAttribute('data-id', '42');

CREATING & REMOVING:
  const div = document.createElement('div');
  div.textContent = 'Hello';
  parent.appendChild(div);
  parent.removeChild(div);

EVENTS:
  el.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();   // stop default action (form submit, link follow)
    e.stopPropagation();  // stop bubbling up to parent
    console.log(e.target); // element that was clicked
  });

EVENT DELEGATION:
  // Instead of adding listener to each child, add one to parent:
  ul.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    if (e.target.tagName === 'LI') {
      handle(e.target);
    }
  });

COMMON EVENTS: click, dblclick, keydown, keyup, input, change, submit, focus, blur, mouseover, resize, scroll, DOMContentLoaded

ES6 (2015) modernised JavaScript. These features are used in every React codebase.

ARROW FUNCTIONS:
  // Traditional
  function add(a, b) { return a + b; }
  // Arrow
  const add = (a, b) => a + b;
  // Single param — no parens needed
  const double = n => n * 2;
  // Key difference: arrow functions do NOT have their own 'this'

DESTRUCTURING:
  const { name, age } = person;         // object
  const [first, , third] = array;       // array (skip index 1)
  const { a: alias } = obj;            // rename while destructuring

SPREAD & REST:
  const merged = { ...obj1, ...obj2 };  // spread objects
  const arr2   = [...arr1, 4, 5];       // spread arrays
  function sum(...nums) { }             // rest: collect into array

TEMPLATE LITERALS:
  const msg = `Hello ${name}, you are ${age} years old`;

PROMISES:
  const p = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => resolve('done'), 1000);
  });
  p.then(val => console.log(val))
   .catch(err => console.error(err));

ASYNC/AWAIT:
  async function fetchData() {
    try {
      const res = await fetch('/api/data');
      const json = await res.json();
      return json;
    } catch (err) {
      console.error(err);
    }
  }

MODULES (ESM):
  // export (named)
  export const PI = 3.14;
  export function greet(name) { }
  // export (default)
  export default class App { }
  // import
  import App, { PI, greet } from './module.js';

OTHER ES6+:
• Optional chaining: obj?.prop?.nested
• Nullish coalescing: value ?? 'default'
• Map, Set, WeakMap, WeakSet
• Symbol, Iterator, Generator

ASYNCHRONOUS PROGRAMMING:

Why async? Browser JS is single-threaded. Network calls, timers, and I/O are offloaded to browser APIs and handled via the Event Loop when complete.

Event Loop flow:
  Call Stack → Web APIs → Callback Queue → Call Stack (when empty)
  Microtasks (Promises) → Macrotasks (setTimeout)

FETCH API:
  // GET
  fetch('https://api.example.com/users')
    .then(res => {
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error('HTTP ' + res.status);
      return res.json();
    })
    .then(data => console.log(data))
    .catch(err => console.error(err));

  // POST
  fetch('/api/users', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json',
               'Authorization': 'Bearer ' + token },
    body: JSON.stringify({ name: 'Alice', age: 25 })
  }).then(res => res.json());

  // Async/await style (cleaner)
  async function createUser(user) {
    const res = await fetch('/api/users', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify(user)
    });
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(await res.text());
    return res.json();
  }

PROMISE COMBINATORS:
  Promise.all([p1, p2, p3])      // wait for ALL — fails fast on any rejection
  Promise.allSettled([p1, p2])   // wait for ALL — get all results/errors
  Promise.race([p1, p2])         // first to settle wins
  Promise.any([p1, p2])          // first to RESOLVE wins

ERROR HANDLING PATTERN:
  fetch() only rejects on network failure, NOT on 4xx/5xx.
  Always check res.ok or res.status.

LIFECYCLE (class component mental model):
  Mount   → componentDidMount   (run once after render)
  Update  → componentDidUpdate  (run after re-render)
  Unmount → componentWillUnmount (cleanup)

HOOKS (modern equivalent):

useState — local state
  const [value, setValue] = useState(initial);

useEffect — side effects (data fetch, subscriptions, DOM manipulation)
  useEffect(() => {
    // Runs after render
    fetchData().then(setData);

    return () => {
      // Cleanup: runs before unmount or before re-running effect
      subscription.unsubscribe();
    };
  }, [dependency1, dependency2]);  // re-runs when deps change
  // [] = run once on mount only
  // no array = run after every render

useRef — mutable ref that does NOT cause re-render
  const inputRef = useRef(null);
  <input ref={inputRef} />
  inputRef.current.focus(); // access DOM node

useCallback — memoize a function reference
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => doSomething(id), [id]);

useMemo — memoize a computed value
  const expensiveResult = useMemo(() => compute(data), [data]);

CUSTOM HOOKS:
  Reusable logic extracted into a function prefixed with 'use'.
  function useFetch(url) {
    const [data, setData] = useState(null);
    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
    useEffect(() => {
      fetch(url).then(r => r.json()).then(d => {
        setData(d);
        setLoading(false);
      });
    }, [url]);
    return { data, loading };
  }

RULES OF HOOKS:
• Only call hooks at the top level (not inside loops/conditions)
• Only call hooks from React functions (not regular JS functions)

PROBLEM WITH PROP DRILLING:
Passing props through many levels:
  App → Layout → Main → Section → Card → Button
Becomes messy when deeply nested components need the same data.

CONTEXT API (built into React):
  // 1. Create context
  const ThemeContext = createContext('light');

  // 2. Provide it
  function App() {
    const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light');
    return (
      <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}>
        <Layout />
      </ThemeContext.Provider>
    );
  }

  // 3. Consume anywhere in tree
  function Button() {
    const { theme } = useContext(ThemeContext);
    return <button className={theme}>Click</button>;
  }

WHEN TO USE CONTEXT: global data like theme, auth user, language, settings.

REDUX:
For complex state with many interactions. Used in large enterprise apps.
  Store: single source of truth for all app state
  Action: plain object describing what happened { type: 'ADD_ITEM', payload: item }
  Reducer: pure function (state, action) => newState
  Dispatch: send an action to the store

REDUX TOOLKIT (modern Redux):
  import { createSlice, configureStore } from '@reduxjs/toolkit';
  const counterSlice = createSlice({
    name: 'counter',
    initialState: { value: 0 },
    reducers: {
      increment: state => { state.value += 1; }
    }
  });

WHEN TO USE REDUX:
• Multiple components need to share and mutate the same state
• Complex state transitions that need to be tracked/debugged
• Large teams where predictable state flow matters

ALTERNATIVES: Zustand (lightweight), Jotai, React Query (for server state)

React Router enables client-side routing — navigating between pages without a full page reload.

INSTALL: npm install react-router-dom

BASIC SETUP:
  import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route, Link, useNavigate, useParams } from 'react-router-dom';

  function App() {
    return (
      <BrowserRouter>
        <Routes>
          <Route path="/"           element={<Home />} />
          <Route path="/about"      element={<About />} />
          <Route path="/users/:id"  element={<UserDetail />} />
          <Route path="*"           element={<NotFound />} />
        </Routes>
      </BrowserRouter>
    );
  }

NAVIGATION:
  // Declarative (renders <a> tag)
  <Link to="/about">About</Link>

  // Programmatic
  const navigate = useNavigate();
  navigate('/dashboard');         // push
  navigate(-1);                   // go back
  navigate('/login', { replace: true }); // replace history entry

ROUTE PARAMS:
  // Route: /users/:id
  const { id } = useParams();  // id = '42' for /users/42

QUERY PARAMS:
  const [searchParams] = useSearchParams();
  const query = searchParams.get('q');  // /search?q=react

NESTED ROUTES:
  <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />}>
    <Route path="profile" element={<Profile />} />
    <Route path="settings" element={<Settings />} />
  </Route>
  // Dashboard uses <Outlet /> to render nested route

PROTECTED ROUTES:
  function PrivateRoute({ children }) {
    const { user } = useAuth();
    return user ? children : <Navigate to="/login" />;
  }

React apps consume Spring Boot REST APIs. Two common approaches:

FETCH (built-in, no install):
  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('http://localhost:8080/api/users')
      .then(res => {
        if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed');
        return res.json();
      })
      .then(data => setUsers(data))
      .catch(err => setError(err.message));
  }, []);

AXIOS (install: npm install axios):
  import axios from 'axios';
  useEffect(() => {
    axios.get('http://localhost:8080/api/users')
      .then(res => setUsers(res.data))  // res.data is already parsed
      .catch(err => setError(err.message));
  }, []);

AXIOS ADVANTAGES OVER FETCH:
• Automatic JSON parsing (no .json() call)
• Automatic error for 4xx/5xx status
• Request/Response interceptors (add auth headers globally)
• Request cancellation with AbortController
• Base URL configuration

AXIOS INSTANCE (for Spring Boot):
  const api = axios.create({
    baseURL: 'http://localhost:8080/api',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' }
  });
  // Interceptor to add JWT token
  api.interceptors.request.use(config => {
    const token = localStorage.getItem('token');
    if (token) config.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${token}`;
    return config;
  });

CRUD PATTERN:
  api.get('/users')              // GET all
  api.get('/users/42')           // GET one
  api.post('/users', { name })   // POST create
  api.put('/users/42', data)     // PUT update
  api.delete('/users/42')        // DELETE

LOADING STATE PATTERN:
  const [data, setData]       = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError]     = useState(null);
  // Show loading spinner, then data or error

PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATION:

React.memo — prevent re-render if props unchanged:
  const Card = React.memo(function Card({ title }) {
    return <div>{title}</div>;
  });

useMemo — memoize expensive computation:
  const sortedList = useMemo(() => [...list].sort(), [list]);

useCallback — stable function reference for child components:
  const handleDelete = useCallback((id) => {
    setItems(items.filter(i => i.id !== id));
  }, [items]);

Lazy loading (code splitting):
  const HeavyComponent = React.lazy(() => import('./HeavyComponent'));
  // Wrap in Suspense:
  <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
    <HeavyComponent />
  </Suspense>

Virtualization (for long lists):
  Use react-window or react-virtual to render only visible rows.
  Critical for tables with 1000+ rows.

ERROR BOUNDARIES:
Class component that catches JS errors in its child tree.
  class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
    state = { hasError: false };
    static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
      return { hasError: true };
    }
    componentDidCatch(error, info) {
      logToSentry(error, info);
    }
    render() {
      if (this.state.hasError) return <h1>Something went wrong.</h1>;
      return this.props.children;
    }
  }
  // Usage:
  <ErrorBoundary>
    <MyRiskyComponent />
  </ErrorBoundary>

NOTE: Error boundaries only catch errors during render/lifecycle, not in event handlers or async code.
